04594nam a22006735i 9780292767669DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211996txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927676697 a10.7560/7085012doi  a(DE-B1597)588618  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1435.3.E72bM39 1996 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a972.81/00497422000aMaya Cultural Activism in Guatemala /ced. by R. McKenna Brown, Edward F. Fischer. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcronyms -- t1. Introduction: Maya Cultural Activism in Guatemala -- t2. The Politics of Maya Revindication -- t3. Induced Culture Change as a Strategy for Socioeconomic Development: The Pan-Maya Movement in Guatemala -- t4. Maya Culture and the Politics of Development -- t5. Reading History as Resistance: Maya Public Intellectuals in Guatemala -- t6. The Discourse of Concealment and 1992 -- t7. Old Writing and New Messages: The Role of Hieroglyphic Literacy in Maya Cultural Activism -- t8. The Workshop for Maya on Hieroglyphic Writing -- t9. Maya Clothing and Identity -- t10. Women, Weaving, and Education in Maya Revitalization -- t11. The Mayan Language Loyalty Movement in Guatemala -- t12. The Role of Language Standardization in Revitalization -- t13. Prescriptive Grammar and Kaqchikel Revitalization -- t14. Maya Education: A Historical and Contemporary Analysis of Mayan Language Education Policy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaya Cultural Activism in Guatemala marks a new era in Guatemalan studies by offering an up-to-the-minute look at the pan-Maya movement and the future of the Maya people as they struggle to regain control over their cultural destiny. The successful emergence of what is in some senses a nationalism grounded in ethnicity and language has challenged scholars to reconsider their concepts of nationalism, community, and identity. Editors Edward F. Fischer and R. McKenna Brown have brought together essays by virtually all the leading U.S. experts on contemporary Maya communities and the top Maya scholars working in Guatemala today. Supplementing scholarly analysis of Mayan cultural activism is a position statement originating within the movement and more wide-ranging and personal reflections by anthropologists and linguists who have worked with the Maya over the years. Among the broader issues that come in for examination are the complex relations between U.S. Mayanists and the Mayan cultural movement, efforts to promote literacy in Mayan languages, the significance of woven textiles and native dress, the relations between language and national identity, and the cultural meanings that the present-day Maya have encountered in ancient Mayan texts and hieroglyphic writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthnicityzGuatemala. 0aMayas - Social life and customs. 0aMayasxEthnic identity. 0aMayasxPolitics and government. 0aMayasxSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBrown, R. McKenna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer, Edward F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70850140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767669/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK